channel.description:
This tutorial shows you how to create a server starting from scratch! (Yes this is extremely easy, but this tutorial is aimed for people who don't have as much knowledge about networking and what not!)

NB: Using IO is so much easier then using NIO and a lot of the other major networks.  
    - This is not the best tutorial out there :(
    - Some of this code could be done much better
    - I might of missed something by mistake!
    - Aimed at novice coders who want to create their own servers!



[b]Note:[/b]
- I will show you Login (for 317)
- This is only partially network setup 
- You will need some java knowledge if you want to develop a server from scratch

- Something's may have not been explained; so please feel free to ask me about certain things, functions and any question you may have!

[b]Introduction:[/b]
This tutorial will show you how to use IO networking (library's should already come with java) and setting up a basic client/source connection. You will however need to figure out how to get the client loaded up because some of the higher version servers usually have CRC, update server etc enabled so you will need to work it out.
I will use a few class file because to keep the flow of the server neat and tidy :)

Difficulty: 2/10 
Difficulty finishing off this guide to create a server for your own base on what ever version: 8/10

Recommended: Some basic Java knowledge!

Lets start off...


Start by creating your packages normally consist of
[code]domain.company.applicationName[/code]

e.g
[code] com.mopar.rs2[/code]

for the sake of this tutorial I'll be doing

[code]com.rs2;[/code]

First we need a main class that will run the server which includes all the start up process etc.
Create a new Java file called Server.java or Launch.java or anything similar to that. 

Inside it you will need to declare the main body which is used to run the server.

it should look something like this;

[code]package com.rs2;

public class Launch {

        public static void main(String args[]) {
                try {

                } catch (Exception e) {
                        e.printStackTrace();
                }
        }
}[/code]

Within the catch exception you will need to add [code]new Connect();[/code] so Connect will start once you setup the server. 

Server.java should now look like this:
[code] public class Launch {

        public static void main(String args[]) {
                try {
                      new Connect();
                } catch (Exception e) {
                        e.printStackTrace();
                }
        }[/code]

You should get an error because You have not yet created a Connect.java file yet. That should be it for Launch.java

Next up start by creating the package [code]com.rs2.net[/code] and inside it add Connect.java

[code]public class Connect {

}[/code]

You need to declare the IO class's that will be used so user public class Connect { add

[code]	private ServerSocket serverSocket;
	private Socket socket;[/code]

once you have done that you need to create a constructor for Connect (which will also eliminate the error in Launch)

add 
[code]
public Connect() {

}
[/code]

inside your constructor add 
[code]
		serverSocket = new ServerSocket(43594);
		init();[/code]

what serverSocket = new ServerSocket(43594); does it binds the server to port 43594 (allow it to run on that port)

under your constructor add the init(); method

[code]	private void init() {
		while (true) {
			try {
				socket = serverSocket.accept();
				socket.setTcpNoDelay(true);
				new Thread(new Player(socket)).start();
				Thread.sleep(100);
			} catch (Exception e) {
				e.printStackTrace();
			}
		}
	}[/code]

this basically accepts the connection from the client and process's the login data plus creates a thread for the client.

For the next step (login, player etc) there are many different ways to do this. Just because i'm a noob I'll be doing it a noob way ;)

Create a new package called [code]com.rs2.player[/code] then create a new Java file called Player.java

Because in Connect.java we are using a thread for each clients  you will need to implement Runnable in Player.java 

so your class should look something like this.

[code]public class Player implements Runnable {

@Override 
public void run() {

}

}[/code]

because we implemented Runnable, you will need a run() method.

You will need to declare the IO class's in player so you will need to add:

[code]	
        private Socket socket;
	private DataInputStream input;
	private DataOutputStream output;[/code]

create a constructor in Player and add [code]this.socket = socket;[/code]

Your consturctor should look like so:

[code]	public Player(Socket socket) {
		this.socket = socket;
	}
[/code]

You need to declare some variables for the player so  declare 
[code]	private String username, password;[/code]

add a method for player details;

[code]	public void details(String username, String password) {
		this.username = username;
		this.password = password;
	}[/code]

(you could also create setters and getters if you like)

in you run(); method add

[code]	public void run() {
		try {
			input = new DataInputStream(socket.getInputStream());
			output = new DataOutputStream(socket.getOutputStream());

			new Login().login(this);
			System.out.println("username: " + username + " password: "
					+ password);
		} catch (Exception e) {
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
	}[/code]

^ this will just process the player login

create a new package called [code]com.rs2.util;[/code]


Create a new class called ISAACCipher (credits to Bob Jenkins and Graham Edgecombe)

add everything below inside it.

[code]
package com.kitty.util;

/**
 * <p>
 * An implementation of an ISAAC cipher. See <a
 * href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISAAC_(cipher)">
 * http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISAAC_(cipher)</a> for more information.
 * </p>
 * <p/>
 * <p>
 * This implementation is based on the one written by Bob Jenkins, which is
 * available at <a href="http://www.burtleburtle.net/bob/java/rand/Rand.java">
 * http://www.burtleburtle.net/bob/java/rand/Rand.java</a>.
 * </p>
 * 
 * @author Graham Edgecombe
 */
public class ISAACCipher {

	/**
	 * The golden ratio.
	 */
	public static final int RATIO = 0x9e3779b9;

	/**
	 * The log of the size of the results and memory arrays.
	 */
	public static final int SIZE_LOG = 8;

	/**
	 * The size of the results and memory arrays.
	 */
	public static final int SIZE = 1 << SIZE_LOG;

	/**
	 * For pseudorandom lookup.
	 */
	public static final int MASK = (SIZE - 1) << 2;

	/**
	 * The count through the results.
	 */
	private int count = 0;

	/**
	 * The results.
	 */
	private int results[] = new int[SIZE];

	/**
	 * The internal memory state.
	 */
	private int memory[] = new int[SIZE];

	/**
	 * The accumulator.
	 */
	private int a;

	/**
	 * The last result.
	 */
	private int b;

	/**
	 * The counter.
	 */
	private int c;

	/**
	 * Creates the ISAAC cipher.
	 * 
	 * @param seed
	 *            The seed.
	 */
	public ISAACCipher(int[] seed) {
		for (int i = 0; i < seed.length; i++) {
			results[i] = seed[i];
		}
		init(true);
	}

	/**
	 * Gets the next value.
	 * 
	 * @return The next value.
	 */
	public int getNextValue() {
		if (count-- == 0) {
			isaac();
			count = SIZE - 1;
		}
		return results[count];
	}

	/**
	 * Generates 256 results.
	 */
	public void isaac() {
		int i, j, x, y;
		b += ++c;
		for (i = 0, j = SIZE / 2; i < SIZE / 2;) {
			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a << 13;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;

			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a >>> 6;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;

			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a << 2;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;

			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a >>> 16;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;
		}
		for (j = 0; j < SIZE / 2;) {
			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a << 13;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;

			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a >>> 6;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;

			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a << 2;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;

			x = memory[i];
			a ^= a >>> 16;
			a += memory[j++];
			memory[i] = y = memory[(x & MASK) >> 2] + a + b;
			results[i++] = b = memory[((y >> SIZE_LOG) & MASK) >> 2] + x;
		}
	}

	/**
	 * Initialises the ISAAC.
	 * 
	 * @param flag
	 *            Flag indicating if we should perform a second pass.
	 */
	public void init(boolean flag) {
		int i;
		int a, b, c, d, e, f, g, h;
		a = b = c = d = e = f = g = h = RATIO;
		for (i = 0; i < 4; ++i) {
			a ^= b << 11;
			d += a;
			b += c;
			b ^= c >>> 2;
			e += b;
			c += d;
			c ^= d << 8;
			f += c;
			d += e;
			d ^= e >>> 16;
			g += d;
			e += f;
			e ^= f << 10;
			h += e;
			f += g;
			f ^= g >>> 4;
			a += f;
			g += h;
			g ^= h << 8;
			b += g;
			h += a;
			h ^= a >>> 9;
			c += h;
			a += b;
		}
		for (i = 0; i < SIZE; i += 8) {
			if (flag) {
				a += results[i];
				b += results[i + 1];
				c += results[i + 2];
				d += results[i + 3];
				e += results[i + 4];
				f += results[i + 5];
				g += results[i + 6];
				h += results[i + 7];
			}
			a ^= b << 11;
			d += a;
			b += c;
			b ^= c >>> 2;
			e += b;
			c += d;
			c ^= d << 8;
			f += c;
			d += e;
			d ^= e >>> 16;
			g += d;
			e += f;
			e ^= f << 10;
			h += e;
			f += g;
			f ^= g >>> 4;
			a += f;
			g += h;
			g ^= h << 8;
			b += g;
			h += a;
			h ^= a >>> 9;
			c += h;
			a += b;
			memory[i] = a;
			memory[i + 1] = b;
			memory[i + 2] = c;
			memory[i + 3] = d;
			memory[i + 4] = e;
			memory[i + 5] = f;
			memory[i + 6] = g;
			memory[i + 7] = h;
		}
		if (flag) {
			for (i = 0; i < SIZE; i += 8) {
				a += memory[i];
				b += memory[i + 1];
				c += memory[i + 2];
				d += memory[i + 3];
				e += memory[i + 4];
				f += memory[i + 5];
				g += memory[i + 6];
				h += memory[i + 7];
				a ^= b << 11;
				d += a;
				b += c;
				b ^= c >>> 2;
				e += b;
				c += d;
				c ^= d << 8;
				f += c;
				d += e;
				d ^= e >>> 16;
				g += d;
				e += f;
				e ^= f << 10;
				h += e;
				f += g;
				f ^= g >>> 4;
				a += f;
				g += h;
				g ^= h << 8;
				b += g;
				h += a;
				h ^= a >>> 9;
				c += h;
				a += b;
				memory[i] = a;
				memory[i + 1] = b;
				memory[i + 2] = c;
				memory[i + 3] = d;
				memory[i + 4] = e;
				memory[i + 5] = f;
				memory[i + 6] = g;
				memory[i + 7] = h;
			}
		}
		isaac();
		count = SIZE;
	}

}
[/code]

create a new package called [code]com.rs2.io;[/code]

Make a java file called Stream

inside Stream add 

these 2 methods
[code]
	public static String readString(DataInputStream input) throws IOException {
		byte temp;
		StringBuilder b = new StringBuilder();
		while ((temp = (byte) input.readByte()) != 10) {
			b.append((char) temp);
		}
		return b.toString();
	}

	public static void writeString(DataOutputStream output, String string)
			throws IOException {
		for (byte value : string.getBytes()) {
			output.writeByte(value);
		}
		output.writeByte(10);
	}[/code]


Go back to Player.java and declare
[code]
	private ISAACCipher in;
	private ISAACCipher out;
[/code]

then add this:
[code]
	public DataInputStream getInputStream() {
		return input;
	}

	public DataOutputStream getOutputStream() {
		return output;
	}

